---
import Layout from "../../layouts/Layout.astro";
import LessonShell from "../../components/LessonShell.astro";
import Reveal from "../../components/Reveal.astro";
import { LESSONS } from "../../data/curriculum";

const lesson = LESSONS.find((l) => l.id === "chat-artifacts")!;
---

<Layout title={`${lesson.title} · Learn Claude`}>
  <main>
    <LessonShell lesson={lesson}>
      <p>
        When Claude produces something <strong>longer or self-contained</strong> — a document, a chunk of code, a small webpage —
        it splits it out into a side panel called an <strong>artifact</strong>. The chat keeps the running conversation;
        the artifact holds the thing you're building.
      </p>

      <h2>Why this matters</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>You don't lose it in the scrollback.</strong> The artifact stays pinned to the side.</li>
        <li><strong>You can iterate.</strong> "Make it shorter", "Use bullet points", "Try a friendlier tone" — Claude updates the artifact in place.</li>
        <li><strong>You can take it with you.</strong> Copy, download, or (for code) preview it live.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Try this in a real chat</h2>
      <ol class="steps">
        <li>Open <a href="https://claude.ai" target="_blank" rel="noopener">claude.ai</a>.</li>
        <li>Type: <em>"Write a one-page brief for moving from Hong Kong to Singapore. Cover visa, schools, cost of living."</em></li>
        <li>Watch the right side. The brief appears there, not in the chat thread.</li>
        <li>Now say: <em>"Add a section on transport."</em> The artifact updates.</li>
      </ol>

      <div class="callout">
        <strong>What counts as an artifact?</strong> Anything that's a <em>thing you'd want to keep</em>: a long write-up,
        a working snippet of code, an HTML page you can preview, a flowchart, a table. Casual chat replies stay in the conversation.
      </div>

      <h2>Artifacts you'll see most often</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Documents</strong> — letters, briefs, summaries, plans.</li>
        <li><strong>Code</strong> — a single file you can copy or run.</li>
        <li><strong>Mini-apps</strong> — interactive HTML that runs in a preview pane.</li>
        <li><strong>Diagrams</strong> — flowcharts and sequence diagrams in Mermaid format.</li>
      </ul>

      <Reveal q="Can I edit an artifact directly?">
        Yes — there's usually an "edit" mode on the artifact. Or just ask in chat: "Change the second paragraph to..."
      </Reveal>
      <Reveal q="Does my artifact persist?">
        Yes. It's saved with the chat. Reopen the conversation later and the artifact is right there.
      </Reveal>
    </LessonShell>
  </main>
</Layout>
